{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17621496","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17621496"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:54:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:54:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16740"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16740","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16740"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.66,0.13,0,0.22]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9431"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106410"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9431","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9431"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16740"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88865"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9839"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22296"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39206"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106410","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106410"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ABO blood group system is determined by the presence or absence of specific antigens on red blood cells and their corresponding antibodies in plasma.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the antigen and antibody profile of type O blood?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["B antigen with anti-A antibody","Anti-A and anti-B antibodies present","A and B antigens without antibodies","A antigen with anti-B antibody","Neither antigens nor antibodies"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EType O blood is characterised by the absence of both A and B antigens on red blood cells, with both \u003Cstrong\u003Eanti-A and anti-B antibodies present\u003C/strong\u003E in the plasma. This makes type O individuals universal donors for red blood cells as there are no A or B antigens that could react with recipient antibodies. However, type O individuals can only receive blood from type O donors as they have anti-A and anti-B antibodies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are incorrect because:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EB antigen with anti-A antibody\u003C/strong\u003E describes type B blood\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA and B antigens without antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E describes type AB blood\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA antigen with anti-B antibody\u003C/strong\u003E describes type A blood\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeither antigens nor antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E - this combination does not exist; the absence of A and B antigens always results in the presence of corresponding antibodies\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe following table summarises the ABO blood group system:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cdiv class=\u0022table-container\u0022\u003E\u003Ctable\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Cth\u003EBlood Type\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003EAntigens on Red Blood Cells\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003EAntibodies in Plasma\u003C/th\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EType A\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EA antigen\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EAnti-B antibody\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EType B\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EB antigen\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EAnti-A antibody\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EType AB\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EA and B antigens\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003ENo antibodies\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EType O\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003ENo antigens\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EAnti-A and anti-B antibodies\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003C/table\u003E\u003C/div\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The ABO blood group system consists of A and B antigens on red blood cells with corresponding anti-A and anti-B antibodies in plasma.","Type O individuals have neither A nor B antigens but have both anti-A and anti-B antibodies.","Type O individuals are universal red blood cell donors but can only receive type O blood."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88865"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16740"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88865","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88865"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-19T16:59:25+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-19T17:01:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9431"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106410"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"ite